javascriopt class : carJavaScript Classes : The Blueprint That Finally Made Sense to Me
One simple idea: a class is just a blueprint.
Think about an architect. They don’t build a house from scratch every single time they draw one blueprint, and then use it to build as many similar houses/structures as they want. A JavaScript class works the same way. You define the blueprint once, and then create as many objects from it as you need.
Once that clicked, everything else will start making sense. Here’s the breakdown once you get that you’ll never forget .
Why This Actually Matters (Not Just Interview Trivia)
Before ES6 (2015), JavaScript used constructor functions to do this same job but they were messy and hard to read. Classes cleaned that up, and now they’re the industry standard.
This isn’t just a beginner exercise either. At companies like Google, classes show up everywhere: data models, service layers, UI components (React still supports class components, even though hooks are more common now), and classic design patterns like Singleton and Factory. Understanding this foundation pays off well beyond your first project.
If you’re a fresher, here’s the good news: you don’t need to memorize everything. Focus on constructor → methods → inheritance → super.
The Basic Syntax
class ClassName {
constructor() {
// runs automatically when object is created
} methodName() {
// behaviour
}
}Your First Class
Let’s make this concrete with a Car blueprint:
class Car {
constructor(brand, model) {
this.brand = brand; // property
this.model = model; // property
}
describe() {
console.log(`This car is a ${this.brand} ${this.model}`);
}
}// Creating objects (instances) from the blueprint
const car1 = new Car("Toyota", "Camry");
const car2 = new Car("Tesla", "Model 3");
car1.describe(); // This car is a Toyota Camry
car2.describe(); // This car is a Tesla Model 3The new keyword is what actually builds a fresh object using the blueprint. And this simply refers to whichever object is currently being created in this case, car1 or car2.
The constructor() Method
The constructor is a special method that runs automatically the moment you write new ClassName(). Its whole job is to set up the object's initial properties.
class Person {
constructor(name, age) {
this.name = name;
this.age = age;
}
}
const p1 = new Person("Alice", 22);
console.log(p1.name); // Rahul
console.log(p1.age); // 22Methods: What an Object Can Do
If properties describe what an object has, methods describe what it can do.
class Calculator {
add(a, b) {
return a + b;
}
subtract(a, b) {
return a - b;
}
}
const calc = new Calculator();
console.log(calc.add(5, 3)); // 8
console.log(calc.subtract(5, 3)); // 2Inheritance: Passing the Blueprint Down
One class can inherit properties and methods from another.
Think parent → child. This is where classes start to feel genuinely powerful.
class Animal {
constructor(name) {
this.name = name;
}
speak() {
console.log(`${this.name} makes a sound.`);
}
}
class Dog extends Animal { // Dog inherits from Animal
speak() { // overrides parent method
console.log(`${this.name} barks.`);
}
}
class Cat extends Animal {
speak() {
console.log(`${this.name} meows.`);
}
}
const d = new Dog("Bruno");
const c = new Cat("Whiskers");
d.speak(); // Bruno barks.
c.speak(); // Whiskers meows.Both Dog and Cat reused the same Animal blueprint, but customized their own behavior. That's the whole point of inheritance reuse what makes sense, override what doesn't.
The super Keyword
super lets a child class reach back and call its parent's constructor or methods.
class Vehicle {
constructor(brand) {
this.brand = brand;
}
info() {
console.log(`Brand: ${this.brand}`);
}
}
class Bike extends Vehicle {
constructor(brand, type) {
super(brand); // calls Vehicle's constructor
this.type = type;
}
info() {
super.info(); // calls Vehicle's info()
console.log(`Type: ${this.type}`);
}
}
const b = new Bike("Honda", "Sports");
b.info();
// Brand: Honda
// Type: SportsWithout super(brand), the Bike class would have no way to set up the brand property it inherited from Vehicle. It's the bridge between parent and child.
Static Methods
Static methods belong to the class itself, not to any individual object so you call them directly on the class, no newrequired.
class MathHelper {
static square(n) {
return n * n;
}
}
console.log(MathHelper.square(4)); // 16You’ll see this pattern constantly in utility and helper classes across real codebases.
Getters and Setters
Getters and setters give you control over how a property is read or written instead of just exposing raw data.
class Student {
constructor(name) {
this._name = name; // _ means "internal" by convention
}
get name() {
return this._name.toUpperCase(); // transforms on read
}
set name(newName) {
if (newName.length < 2) {
console.log("Name too short!");
return;
}
this._name = newName;
}
}
const s = new Student("rahul");
console.log(s.name); // RAHUL (getter runs)
s.name = "R"; // Name too short! (setter validates)
s.name = "Ravi";
console.log(s.name); // RAVIPrivate Fields (Modern JS : ES2022)
Use # to make a field genuinely private it can't be accessed from outside the class at all.
class BankAccount {
#balance = 0; // private field deposit(amount) {
this.#balance += amount;
} getBalance() {
return this.#balance;
}
}const acc = new BankAccount();
acc.deposit(1000);
console.log(acc.getBalance()); // 1000
console.log(acc.#balance); // ❌ SyntaxError — can't access directlyBig companies lean on this heavily in production code to protect sensitive data from being touched where it shouldn’t be.
Quick Recap

• constructor() → sets up initial data

• Methods → define behavior

• Static methods → class-level utilities, no object needed

• Getters / setters → controlled property access

• extends + super → inheritance, parent to child
If you only remember one thing from this post, remember the blueprint. Everything else inheritance, super, static methods is just extra tooling built on top of that one idea.

What tripped you up first when you were learning classes this, super, or private fields? Let me know in the comments I'm curious if my experience was a one-off or if everyone hits the same wall.
